\v 27 It brushes aside iron like straw, and bronze like rotten wood.  
\v 28 Arrows cannot make it run away; stones from slingshots are like pieces of stubble.  
\v 29 Clubs are also treated like stubble; it laughs at the sound made by flying spears.  
\v 30 Its underparts are covered with points as sharp as broken pots; when it drags itself through the mud it leaves marks like \w a|strong="H3068"\w* threshing sledge.\f + \fr 41:30 \ft Threshing sledge: a board with sharp spikes for threshing grain. \f*  
\v 31 It churns up the sea like water in \w a|strong="H3068"\w* boiling pot, like \w a|strong="H3068"\w* steaming bowl when ointment is mixed.  
\v 32 It leaves \w a|strong="H3068"\w* glistening wake behind it as if the sea had white hair.  
\v 33 There is nothing on earth like it: \w a|strong="H3068"\w* creature that has no fear.  
\v 34 It looks down on all other creatures. It is the proudest of all.”   
\b  
\c 42  
\p
\v 1 \w Then|strong="H6030"\w* Job \w answered|strong="H6030"\w* \w the|strong="H3068"\w* \w Lord|strong="H3068"\w*.  
